Q1

a

\[\hat{Y}=\begin{cases} 0 & \text{ if } x= 0\\ 1 & \text{ if } x= 1\\ 1 & \text{ if } x= 2 \end{cases}\]

(-2 -1)^2 * 1/6 + (2-1)^2*1/2
## [1] 2

MSPE \(=\mathbb{E}((Y-\hat{Y})^2) = 2\)

b

muy = c(-2,0,1,2) %*% c(1/6,1/6,1/6,1/2)
mux = c(2,0,1,2) %*% c(1/6,1/6,1/6,1/2)
varx = c(4,0,1,4) %*% c(1/6,1/6,1/6,1/2) - mux^2
# when y >= 0
covxy = c(2*-2,0,1,4) %*% c(1/6,1/6,1/6,1/2) - muy * mux
cat("mux is:",mux,";muy:",muy,"cov(x,y):",covxy,'\n')
## mux is: 1.5 ;muy: 0.8333333 cov(x,y): 0.25
cat("Y hat is " ,muy + (covxy * (-mux)/varx), "+",covxy/varx,"X")
## Y hat is  0.1904762 + 0.4285714 X
yhat2 = as.vector(muy + (covxy * (-mux)/varx) + covxy/varx*c(0,1,2))
## Warning in covxy/varx * c(0, 1, 2): Recycling array of length 1 in array-vector arithmetic is deprecated.
##   Use c() or as.vector() instead.
## Warning in muy + (covxy * (-mux)/varx) + covxy/varx * c(0, 1, 2): Recycling array of length 1 in array-vector arithmetic is deprecated.
##   Use c() or as.vector() instead.
yhat2 
## [1] 0.1904762 0.6190476 1.0476190

\(\hat{Y} = \mu_Y Y+\Sigma(Y,X)\Sigma(X)^{-1}(X-\mu_X)\)\ \(\hat{Y} = 0.1904762 + 0.4285714 X\) \[\hat{Y}=\begin{cases} 0.1904762 & \text{ if } x= 0\\ 0.6190476 & \text{ if } x= 1\\ 1.0476190 & \text{ if } x= 2 \end{cases}\]

# calculating MSPE
mspe = c(0.1904762^2, (1- 0.6190476)^2, (2 - 1.0476190)^2,
         (-2 - 1.0476190)^2) %*% c(1/6,1/6,1/2,1/6)
cat("MSPE:",mspe)
## MSPE: 2.031746

c

Because the MSPE is optimal when \(\mu_x = \mu_y = 0\). We didnt center R.V. X and Y.

Q2

a

\(\gamma(k) = cov(Y_t,Y_{t-k}) = cov(\phi_1(Y_{t-1}-\mu)+\phi_2(Y_{t-2}-\mu)+\epsilon_t,Y_{t-k})\\\) \(= cov(\phi_1Y_{t-1},Y_{t-k})+cov(\phi_2Y_{t-2},Y_{t-k}) + 0\\\) \(= \phi_1\gamma(k-1) + \phi_2\gamma(k-2)\\\)

Divide \(\gamma(0)\) on both left side and right side, gives us

\(\rho(k) = \phi_1\rho(k-1) + \phi_2\rho(k-2)\\ \square\)

b

Because \(\rho(0) = 1\) for time series sequence \(Y_t, \forall t\) Applying the result when k =1 and 2 gives us \(\rho(1) = \rho(0)\phi_1 +\rho(1)\phi_2\) \(\rho(2) = \rho(1)\phi_1 +\rho(0)\phi_2\) Therefore (\(\phi_1,\phi_2\)) solves this linear system. \(\square\)

c

rho = matrix(c(.3,.2),nrow = 2, ncol =1)
sqr_mtx = matrix(c(1,.3,.3,1), 2,2)
res = solve(sqr_mtx) %*% rho
print(res)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.2637363
## [2,] 0.1208791
phi1 = res[1]
phi2 = res[2]
phi3 = c(.2,.3) %*% res
cat("Phi1 is",phi1,"\nPhi2 is",phi2,"\n")
## Phi1 is 0.2637363 
## Phi2 is 0.1208791
cat("Phi3 is",phi3)
## Phi3 is 0.08901099

## The following object is masked from 'package:forecast':
## 
##     BoxCox
root = './datasets/'
file = paste(root,'RUT_03_2015-03_2019.csv', sep ="")
df = read.csv(file)
n = dim(df)[1]
r = df$Adj.Close[-1]/df$Adj.Close[-n] - 1
acf(as.vector(r), lag =20)

# box-Ljng test
Box.test(r, lag = 10, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  r
## X-squared = 11.605, df = 10, p-value = 0.3124

The p-value of Box-Ljung test is 0.3124, which indicates that we cannot reject the null hypothesis. So we have accept the null that the auto correlation are all zeros out to lag 10. From the ACF plot, we dont see any big violations of autocorrelation within the 95% confidence interval till lag = 20. This shows that there is no strong auto-correlation on the sequence. ## b

RUT_ar = ar(r, aic= TRUE, order.max = 6, method = "mle")
RUT_ar
## 
## Call:
## ar(x = r, aic = TRUE, order.max = 6, method = "mle")

# fit the model with ARIMA

                  method = "ML")
temp_df = data.frame(X = RUT_arima$residuals)
p <- ggplot(temp_df, aes(sample = X))
p + stat_qq() +

       y = "Sample quantile")

# Box_Ljung test
Box.test(residuals(RUT_arima), lag = 10, type = "Ljung-Box", fitdf = 4)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  residuals(RUT_arima)
## X-squared = 2.8779, df = 6, p-value = 0.824
acf(as.vector(residuals(RUT_arima)), lag =10, main = "ACF of Residuals")

LBQPlot(residuals(RUT_arima))

checkresiduals(RUT_arima)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(4,0,0) with non-zero mean
## Q* = 2.8779, df = 5, p-value = 0.7188
## 
## Model df: 5.   Total lags used: 10
# auto.arima(r, max.p = 20,max.q = 0,d=0 ,ic = "aic")

The AR model picks the order p = 4. Numerical test of Box-Ljung indicates that with order p = 4, lag = 10 , there is no auto-correlation in the residuals. Graphic plot on Box-Ljung test shows that all p-values are above the 95% interval, which means there is no correlation left in the model.The QQ plot on the residuals shows a bad approximation on its normality, as most of the points locate along the line. But its worth noticing that the residuals are heavy tailed, which means it has more density on its tails.

library(tseries)
f = forecast(RUT_arima, h =12)
n = dim(df)[1]
new_date = seq.Date(as.Date(df$Date)[n], length = 12, by = "week")
upper = f$upper[13:24]
lower = f$lower[13:24]
temp = data.frame(Date = new_date, lower = lower, upper = upper, y = f$mean)
new_date = append(df$Date,as.character(new_date))[-1]
new_return = c(r, f$mean)
new_df = data.frame(Date = new_date, y = new_return)
p = ggplot(new_df) +
  geom_line(aes(as.Date(Date), y),
            color = "black",
            size  = 0.5)+
  geom_line(data = temp,
                          aes(Date, y),
                          color = "red",
                          size  = 1) + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(x = as.Date(Date), ymin = c(r,lower), 
                  ymax = c(r, upper)),
              fill = "grey70", alpha = 0.5)+
  labs(title = "AR p = 4 Prediction on Return",
       x = "Date",
       y = "Return")
p

checkresiduals(arma_fit)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(1,1,0)
## Q* = 46.243, df = 9, p-value = 5.427e-07
## 
## Model df: 1.   Total lags used: 10
Box.test(residuals(arma_fit), lag = 10, type = "Ljung-Box", fitdf = 2)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  residuals(arma_fit)
## X-squared = 46.243, df = 8, p-value = 2.137e-07
LBQPlot(residuals(arma_fit))

Arma reuslt shows that the best pick for order is p = 1, q = 1, and the residuals plot implies a bad fit because most of the points are below the 95% interval. In addition, the ACF plot shows strong auto-correlation when lag is small. Residuals doesnt have normalty as well, its quite right skewed. In summary, ARMA model is not a good fit. ## e
